---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const siteUrl = Astro.site?.href ?? "https://paddletoday.com/";
const websiteId = new URL("/#website", siteUrl).href;
const organizationId = new URL("/#organization", siteUrl).href;
const aboutUrl = new URL("/about/", siteUrl).href;
const aboutStructuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  "@id": `${aboutUrl}#about-page`,
  name: "About Paddle Today",
  description:
    "Learn how Paddle Today ranks paddling routes, checks river and weather data, and explains when a recommendation needs extra caution.",
  url: aboutUrl,
  isPartOf: {
    "@id": websiteId,
  },
  about: {
    "@id": organizationId,
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Paddle Today | How Route Scores Work"
  description="Learn how Paddle Today ranks paddling routes, checks river and weather data, and explains when a recommendation needs extra caution."
  structuredData={aboutStructuredData}
>
  <section class="info-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">About Paddle Today</p>
    <h1>About Paddle Today</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      Paddle Today is for river paddlers who want to find the best paddling
      options today without bouncing between gauges, maps, weather forecasts,
      and river notes.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      River and route coverage starts in the Midwest and focuses first on the
      routes with the strongest gauge stories, clearest access info, and most
      trustworthy source material. Currently this consists of popular routes in
      Minnesota, Wisconsin, and Iowa, with more rivers added as the data quality
      supports it.
    </p>
    <p></p>
    <p class="muted">
      This project is new and still changing quickly, with direction shaped by
      community feedback.
    </p>
    <div class="info-hero__actions">
      <a class="river-link river-link--inline" href="/contact/">Provide feedback</a>
      <a
        class="river-link river-link--inline river-link--ghost"
        href="/request-river/">Request a route</a
      >
    </div>
  </section>

  <section
    class="info-grid info-grid--about-scores"
    aria-label="How Paddle Today scores routes"
  >
    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Scores</p>
      <h2>How Scoring Works</h2>
      <p class="muted about-score-card__intro">
        <strong>Bottom line:</strong> Water level/flow decides if a river is paddleable.
        Weather and other factors increase or decrease the score from there.
      </p>
      <table class="about-score-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Score</th>
            <th scope="col">What it usually means</th>
            <th scope="col">Loose qualifications</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Strong</th>
            <td>Near ideal conditions</td>
            <td>Water in range + low weather risk + solid route support</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Good</th>
            <td>Solid option</td>
            <td
              >Workable water with one or two detractors such as light rain or
              low temperature</td
            >
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Fair</th>
            <td>Runnable with tougher conditions or unknowns</td>
            <td
              >Water in range but weather, thin data, or route cautions pulling
              it down</td
            >
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">No-go</th>
            <td>Not a good call today</td>
            <td
              >Gauge clearly out of range or the overall risk stack is too high
              (storms, ice, closures, obstructions, etc.)</td
            >
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="muted">
        Everything starts with enough water to paddle. From there, the score
        drops for storms, wind, cold air or water, incoming rain, or thin
        support data.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Coverage</p>
      <h2>Adding new routes</h2>
      <p class="muted about-coverage-card__intro">
        Not every river makes sense for the site yet. To keep the
        recommendations trustworthy, I only add routes that meet three basic
        requirements:
      </p>
      <ul class="compact-list about-coverage-card__list">
        <li>
          A reliable <strong>USGS gauge</strong> (or equivalent live reading)
        </li>
        <li>Known usable/preferred water levels</li>
        <li>Clear put-in and take-out coordinates</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="info-panel">
    <p class="eyebrow">Data Sources</p>
    <h2>Most of the site runs on public data and route-specific knowledge.</h2>
    <ul class="compact-list">
      <li><strong>USGS Water Data</strong> (live gauges + trends)</li>
      <li>
        <strong>National Weather Service</strong> (forecasts, wind, temps, storm risk)
      </li>
      <li><strong>State DNR pages</strong> (Minnesota, Wisconsin, Iowa)</li>
      <li><strong>Local trip reports and paddling references</strong></li>
      <li><strong>OpenStreetMap and similar</strong> for access context</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="info-panel">
    <p class="eyebrow">Safety &amp; Limits</p>
    <h2>Use this as a planning tool, not a guarantee.</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      A good score doesn&apos;t mean a river is automatically safe. And a low
      score doesn&apos;t replace your judgment either. Conditions can change
      fast. Rain, debris, strainers, ice, or access issues can turn a
      decent-looking day into a bad one.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      Always do your own due diligence, check the river when you get there, and
      paddle within your skill level.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
